pullRequest.body:
Adds a simple program to render a 2d Array of strings as a table.

- [x] Make formatter output tables in markdown-compliant format.
- [x] Allows specifying alignments for columns
- [x] Refactors the table output of `LongestPole` using this.

---

If you would like: "two-dimensional" instead of "2d".

Can you add a docstring? (Mathlib's docBlame linter requires this anyway.) Something like
```suggestion
/-- Possible alignment modes for each table item: left-aligned, right-aligned and centered. -/
inductive Alignment where

Can you also document the arguments, at least `alignments` (ther others seem obvious enough). Something like the following.
```suggestion
/-- Render a two-dimensional array of `String`s into a markdown-compliant table.
`alignments` describes how to align each table column (default: left-aligned) -/

```suggestion
  -- If no alignments are provided, default to left alignment for all columns.

```suggestion
  -- Compute the maximum width of each column.
Can you use [Array.maxD](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Batteries/Data/Array/Basic.html#Array.maxD) here (with default 0, I guess)?

Not sure that that's a good idea. `maxD` operates on arrays, but we want to operate on the columns of the 2d array, so we would have to transpose. Writing it in an imperative style ultimately feels like it will be more understandable.
Makes sense - let's leave this as-is.

```suggestion
  -- Pad each cell with spaces to match the column width.

This is a matter of taste, but: what do you think about using match here?
```
  match alignments[i] with
    | Alignments.left => cell.rightpad widths[i]!
    | Alignments.right => cell.leftpad widths[i]!
    | Alignments.center =>
            String.replicate ((widths[i]! - cell.length) / 2) ' '
            ++ cell
            ++ String.replicate ((widths[i]! - cell.length + 1) / 2) ' '

Actually: if you'd like to refactor this even more, you could also extract a function
`def align (str : String) (length : Nat) (alignment : Alignment)`.

Update: Originally I thought you'd need the same logic below. Since the code below is slightly different, I'll leave it up to you to decide whether you want to do this.
